english:
  title: Record of the Solitary Stone Pavilion
  author: Seok Muae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    South from Cheolwon County, after walking more than ten thousand paces, there lies a realm of immortals, known by ancient tradition as the Solitary Stone Pavilion. There stands a massive boulder, rising majestically some three hundred feet high, with a circumference of more than ten fathoms. Climbing along its face, one discovers a cavern. By crawling within, the chamber opens like a layered dwelling where a dozen souls might gather. Beside it stands a stone monument—the very marker left by King Jinpyeong of Silla when he came to wander these heights.

    Emerging from the cave and ascending to the summit, the peak spreads flat as a round altar, draped in rough moss like a fringed mat, while green pines stand sentinel, their boughs forming a canopy like a silken parasol. Here too flows a great stream, coursing from the southeast, striking cliffs and rolling stones with the music of ten thousand instruments at once. Where it meets the rocky base, it pools into a dark abyss. To gaze upon it stirs such trembling awe that one wonders if spirits dwell within. The waters overflow and race westward for nearly a league, until striking the southwestern reaches, they turn southward. Both before and behind rise cliff walls like ramparts, while maples, camphor trees, pines, and oaks crown the heights in wild profusion.

    The sublime mystery, the crystalline clarity, the wondrous and strange forms—even one skilled in brush and pigment would struggle to capture their shadow.

    In the autumn of the Year of the Rat, I sought this place with the mountain sage Manhang and others. Upon first sight, my spirit awakened. Upon reaching the summit, all thought dissolved. I sat in speechless rapture, unaware as the sun descended. Then arose in me the sorrow of arriving too late, and the resolve to return. Having thus recorded its appearance, I have also given it voice in verse.
  footnotes:
    - King Jinpyeong of Silla (진평왕) reigned from 579-632 CE, suggesting this site held significance in early Korean history.
    - The 'Year of the Rat' (무자년) refers to a sexagenary cycle; the author appears to have visited in such a year but the specific date requires historical context.
    - The author's name Seok Muae (석무외) suggests a Buddhist monk, common among Korean literary figures of this period.
    - The mention of verses ('시로써 표한다') indicates the original work likely included accompanying poems not provided in this prose record.
